{
  "style": "IEEE",
  "texts": [
    "The protectionist hypothesis argues that polysemous words are easier to process and therefore increase in frequency [1].",
    "Regardless of causal direction, the correlation itself is highly robust across languages [9].A related phenomenon is the frequency-specificity tradeoff: high-frequency words tend to be semantically general (low specificity), while rare words are more specific [11].",
    "This is typically measured as a negative correlation between frequency and semantic variance.",
    "Polysemy Measurement via ClusteringTraditional approaches to measuring polysemy rely on dictionary sense inventories [8], which are subjective and unavailable for model-generated text.",
    "We adopt a data-driven approach: treating word senses as clusters in contextualized embedding space.Given a set of contextualized embeddings {e i } for all instances of word w, we apply DBSCAN clustering [5] with cosine distance."
  ],
